  "nursesNote": "The nurse keeps the psychiatric milieu safe by matching the observation level to the patient's risk: routine checks for low risk, close observation (often every 15 minutes) for higher risk, and one-to-one constant observation at arm's length for the highest risk (such as active suicidal ideation), keeping the patient in view even in the bathroom and never leaving them alone. Contraband that could be used for self-harm is removed: sharps, glass, cords, belts, shoelaces, lighters, and outside medications or substances. Belongings are searched on admission per policy, and items brought by visitors are monitored. Environmental safety includes ligature-resistant fixtures and counting sharps and utensils. The nurse documents all safety checks for accountability and adjusts the observation level as the patient's risk changes.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Match the observation level to the patient's risk",
    "Use one-to-one constant observation for the highest risk",
    "Remove contraband that could be used for self-harm",
    "Search belongings on admission and monitor visitor items",
    "Document all safety checks"
  ],
